  2 & \textit{b} & {Stewart 2011}  &  population & {shared}  & 0.279  &\ding{55} & shared\\ 
  3 & \textit{c} & {Baillie2011}  & individual & NA & NA   & \ding{51}  & young \\ 
       \hline
\end{tabular}
\caption[Groups of Polymorphic Retrotransposons]{\normalsize{\textbf{Groups of Polymorphic Retrotransposons\\}
Group \textit{a,b,} and \textit{c} elements used in this study. Study type indicated whether the data was derived from a large study across multiple populations (population) or from a small study where comparisons were derived from within individuals (individual). The metric of allele frequency was specific for population studies where the frequency of the allele in the population could be determined. Allele sharing was also a metric specific for population studies and referred to whether the elements were identified in one population only (population-specific), or were observed across all populations (shared). Combined refers to the elements which were combined to test the probability of choosing an AS RT versus null expectation. Nickname refers to either the descriptive name of the two groups after being combined (i.e.: "young"), or the uncombined group (shared).}}

\label{table:groups}
\end{table}
Although the allele frequencies of group \textit{c} RTs were unknown, they were identified in Baillie et. al. as being present in the germline insertions. Group \textit{a} and \textit{c} RTs all represent young polymorphic insertions that were significantly less frequent than group \textit{b}. To reduce type II error by increasing sample size the counts were combined across groups \textit{a} and \textit{c} ("young") (table \ref{table:groups} and table \ref{table:youngasbias}).

To determine if there was an antisense bias in newly integrated RTs, the probability of choosing an AS RT in the "young" group was tested versus an expected probability of 0.50 using the binomial sign test. The required sample size to have sufficient power (power = 0.95) to reject the null hypothesis, with an $_\alpha$ of 0.05, was 331 total elements, which our sample size exceeded (N = 1130).  This value was computed using an effect size of 0.09, which was equivalent to effect required to observe the antisense bias of Alu and L1 in the reference genome (table \ref{table:alul1ref}). The hypothesis that young insertions had an AS bias equal to 0.50 could not be rejected (p(AS) = 0.50 ; \num{95}\% CI = 0.47 -- 0.53; p = 0.84). It was noted, that there may have been a bias imparted to the calculation by combining both group \text{a} and \textit{c} RTs in the "young" group. Group \textit{a} RTs were therefore tested separately, at the cost of a reduction in power. The test of group \textit{a} alone also did not result in a p(AS) significantly different from 0.50 (p(AS) = 0.53; \num{95}\% CI = 0.48 -- 0.57; p = 0.20). Although the results of insignificance indicated that young RTs may not have an AS bias, the null hypothesis can not be proven, only rejected \citep{Popper1959,Wilkinson2013}.


