\subsection{Evidence of Purifying Selection on Sense and Antisense Alu}
%stopped here -->
As expected, within sense, antisense, and intergenic Alu, elements on chrX had significantly lower millidiv than those on autosomes, which were significantly less than those on chrY (Appendix table \ref{table:chrsig}). This result showed that chromosomes with heightened ability for purifying selection had elements that were significantly younger, supporting that purifying selection is indeed acting on Alu RTs. In fact, the effect of rate of selection as identified by type of chromosome had a larger effect on element age than the orientation, which could be observed when millidiv values were clustered together (figure \ref{fig:hclustaluchr}). For example, sense Alu on chrY were significantly older than antisense Alu on autosomes. 

%Signs of purifying and positive selection
\subsection{Evidence of Purifying and Positive Selection on Sense and Antisense L1}

         %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{hclust_l1_chr.pdf}
        \caption[Clustering of L1 by Age]{\textbf{Clustering of L1 by Age\\} Red: Sense; Green: Antisense; Black: Intergenic}
        \label{fig:hclustl1chr}
    \end{figure}


When L1 elements were clustered by age, there was a disparity in grouping of elements together by chromosome. L1 elements on autosomes were clustered in one major branch and L1 elements on chrX were clustered on a second major branch (figure \ref{fig:hclustl1chr}). However, L1 on chrY were interspersed within chrX and autosomes. When compared to using Student's t-tests S L1 on chrY were significantly younger than AS L1 on chrY (Appendix table \ref{table:l1chrsig}), indicating a potential difference in selective force acting on S and AS L1 on chrY. 

